   "source": [
    "### 6.1 — What role do weights and biases play in the model?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Weights (W)** control the strength and direction of connections between neurons.  \n",
    "Each neuron computes: `z = W₁x₁ + W₂x₂ + ... + Wₙxₙ + b`  \n",
    "A large positive weight means that feature strongly pushes toward predicting churn.  \n",
    "A large negative weight suppresses that feature's influence.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Biases (b)** act as a threshold shifter — they allow the neuron to fire even when  \n",
    "all inputs are zero, making the model more flexible and capable of fitting any pattern.\n",
    "\n",
    "During **backpropagation**, the gradient of the loss with respect to each weight and bias  \n",
    "is computed. The Adam optimiser then updates these parameters iteratively to minimise  \n",
    "the loss. After training, these learned values *are* the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 6.2 — Why is an activation function required?\n",
    "\n",
    "Without an activation function, each layer performs only a **linear transformation**  \n",
    "(matrix multiplication + bias). Stacking multiple linear layers is still equivalent  \n",
    "to a single linear function — it cannot learn complex patterns like:\n",
    "> *"A customer with high data usage AND low satisfaction AND month-to-month contract is likely to churn"*\n",
    "\n",
    "**ReLU** `f(x) = max(0, x)` introduces **non-linearity**, enabling the network to:  \n",
    "- Learn complex, curved decision boundaries  \n",
    "- Avoid the vanishing gradient problem (unlike sigmoid/tanh)  \n",
    "- Converge faster and scale to deeper networks  \n",
    "\n",
    "Without activation functions, a 10-layer network is mathematically identical to a single linear layer.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 6.3 — What happens when the learning rate is too high or too low?\n",
    "\n",
    "| Scenario | Effect | Observed In |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| **Too High** (e.g. 0.1) | Weight updates overshoot the minimum — loss oscillates or diverges; model may not converge | Exp 2 (0.01): higher loss 0.0014 |\n",
    "| **Too Low** (e.g. 0.00001) | Tiny updates; model learns extremely slowly; may stall before converging | Exp 3 (0.0001): 200 epochs, loss still 0.0256 |\n",
    "| **Just Right** (0.001) | Stable, efficient convergence | Baseline: converged in 81 iter, loss 0.0009 |\n",
    "\n",
    "The learning rate is one of the most critical hyperparameters. Adam helps by adapting  \n",
    "the effective learning rate per parameter, but the initial LR still matters greatly.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 6.4 — Did the model show signs of underfitting or overfitting?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Yes — signs of both were observed:**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Overfitting (Baseline, Exp 1, Exp 2):**  \n",
    "Training accuracy reached 100% while test accuracy was 97.5–98.0%.  \n",
    "The gap indicates the model memorised training data rather than generalising.  \n",
    "More critically, the model achieved zero recall on the churned class — it defaulted  \n",
    "to always predicting \"Retained\", which trivially maximises accuracy.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Underfitting (Exp 3 — Low LR):**  \n",
    "Training accuracy was only 98.94% and the loss remained high (0.0256) after 200 epochs.  \n",
    "The model had not fully learned the training data patterns.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Root cause:**  \n",
    "The extreme class imbalance (98.5% Retained vs 1.5% Churned) is the core problem.  \n",
    "The model found that predicting \"always Retained\" gives ~98.5% accuracy with near-zero loss.  \n",
    "\n",
    "**Recommended solutions:**  \n",
    "1. `class_weight='balanced'` — penalises misclassifying the minority class more  \n",
    "2. SMOTE oversampling — generate synthetic churn samples  \n",
    "3. Lower decision threshold — classify as churn if P(churn) > 0.3 instead of 0.5  \n",
    "4. Use **F1-score** or **ROC-AUC** as the primary evaluation metric, not accuracy"
   ]
